Anomander Rake|Rake|Black-Winged Lord	Son of Darkness and lord of Moon’s Spawn, the Tiste Andii leader whose ancient power, sense of duty, and grim honour shape much of Genabackis’s fate. He is also known as the Black-Winged Lord, a title that alludes to his ability to transform into a great, black-skinned dragon.<br>
Apsal'ara	Also known as the Lady of Thieves, Apsal'ara was an ancient Imass Ascendant. She was killed by Anomander Rake with his sword Dragnipur and her soul was trapped within it for a long time. She is a separate entity from the mortal woman Apsalar, who took her name.<br>
Beru	Also known as the Lord of Storms, an Ascendant and the son of the Elder God Mael. Often invoked by sailors through curses like "Beru fend!" or "by Beru's beard!", he holds dominion over tempests and the rages of the sea.<br>
Burn|Sleeping Goddess	The sleeping goddess whose very dreams are the earth and all life upon it. Her slumber protects the world from her immense power, as her awakening would trigger catastrophic earthquakes and volcanic eruptions. She is slowly being poisoned by the influence of the Crippled God, and her fate is a central concern for many powers in the Malazan world.<br>
Caladan Brood|Brood	Longtime friend and companion of Anomander Rake, a giant man, all muscle and bone, said to be human with Barghast blood. Many thousands of years ago, Brood, Rake, and the Queen of Dreams had walked the land together until Brood chose a more solitary path. When he returned about 1200 years before the current events, he carried Burn's Hammer, an enormous weapon of iron with a copper-wrapped handle said to be capable of shattering mountains. His primary Warren was Tennes, but he also had access to D'riss and High Denul.<br>
Citravaghra	Also called the Man-Leopard or Night Hunter, an Old Beast God who moves with predatory grace and claims humans are the true beasts, appearing to Saeng in the Himatan.<br>
Cotillion|Rope	Cotillion (formerly Dancer), also known as the Rope: God and patron of assassins. He ascended to godhood alongside Shadowthrone (Kellanved) and remains his constant companion and ally. Once a mortal killer, his subtlety and blade now move through the Warren of Shadow. Cotillion is frequently involved in mortal affairs, often manipulating events indirectly to achieve his goals. He is notably connected to Apsalar, whom he possessed and later mentored.<br>
Crippled God|Chained One	Foreign god summoned to the Malazan world by ancient mages of the First Empire. His catastrophic fall shattered his body and fragmented his divine power — fragments that gave rise to the Great Ravens, born like maggots from his rotting corpse-flesh. Chained by the world's existing powers to prevent further devastation, he endured immense suffering for ages while his corrupting influence slowly poisoned Burn, the Sleeping Goddess, threatening all life. His anguish, resentment, and desire for freedom drove him to manipulate mortal pawns across continents, bending events toward his liberation. He commissioned the artist Munug to paint new cards for the Deck of Dragons depicting pain and imperfection, and his Great Ravens carried fragments of his power into every corner of the world.<br>
D'rek	Also known as the Worm of Autumn, a god of decay, rot, and the changing of seasons. D'rek's gender is fluid, and the deity is strongly opposed to the influence of the Crippled God. Their followers believe that all things, in time, must crumble and return to the earth.<br>
Dessembrae	The ascended form of Dassem Ultor, the legendary First Sword of the Malazan Empire. He is worshipped as the Lord of Tragedy and is the patron of soldiers, embodying their grief and loss in war. He is also the figure known as Traveller, who seeks to kill Hood, the Lord of Death.<br>
Draconus	An Elder God known as the Suzerain of Night, one of the most ancient and formidable beings in existence, embodying the power of Darkness through his intimate connection with the realm of Kurald Galain. He served as the consort of Mother Dark and fathered three daughters — the ascendant triplets Envy, Spite, and Malice — and a mortal son, Arathan. Since the age of All Darkness he labored to forge Dragnipur, a sword invested with a terrible finality that traps the souls of those it slays within it, chaining them for eternity to haul a wagon bearing the Gate of Darkness. He stood alongside K'rul and the Sister of Cold Nights at Jacuruku to confront the tyrant Kallor, who cursed him: "what you create will be turned upon you."<br>
Envy|Lady Envy	Ascendant sorceress, daughter of the Elder God Draconus and sister to Spite, her mother thought to be Sheltatha Lore. Tall and slim, with long straight black hair, deep red lips, and stunningly beautiful green eyes darkened by kohl, she wore a flowing white veiled telaba. Possessed of great natural charisma enhanced by sorcery and a seeming ability to read minds, her kiss could enslave those she chose to bend to her will — and even those she did not found her difficult to resist.
Eres'al	An ancient, possibly divine spirit of the Eres, known for her ability to traverse time and influence events to subtly "course-correct" history. Often acting as a motherly entity, she intervenes in the Malazan world when necessary, influencing various characters and plotlines.<br>
Fanderay	Known as "The She-Wolf of Winter," an ancient wolf-god and the mate of Togg. Their reunion is a pivotal event, leading them to occupy the Thrones of the Beast Hold. As ascended beasts, they embody immense power and are deeply connected to the natural world and the House of War.<br>
Gedderone	Lady of Spring and Rebirth, a fertility goddess whose multi-day Gedderone Fête in Darujhistan ushers in the new year with flowers, banners, and the Flaying of Fander dance to welcome the season’s renewal.<br>
Gesler	Falari corporal in the Malazan Coastal Guard, formerly a captain in the Malaz 1st Army under the Old Guard before being demoted during military restructuring. Has flat and wide facial features reflecting north Kanese ancestry with a shaved head. Along with his lifelong friend Stormy, he represents one of the last active members of the Old Guard's Boar Cult.<br>
Gethol	Jaghut Herald of High House Death serving the god Hood, brother of Gothos. Tall gauntly armored figure with pallid skin stretched over taut bones, deeply recessed eyes, and tusks protruding above his lower lip. Wielded two longswords shimmering like liquid gold and possessed magical abilities through the Jaghut Warren of Omtose Phellack.<br>
Gruntle	Daru caravan captain with over twenty years in the mercenary trade, commanding a compact company of guards including Stonny Menackis and Harllo. His reputation for reliability and effectiveness commanded premium rates from merchants and guild factors across Genabackis. Broad-shouldered and physically imposing, he cultivated a sardonic, world-weary manner that belied a deeper capacity for ferocity — those who pushed him far enough discovered he was something considerably more dangerous than his profession suggested, a fact that had not gone unnoticed by Treach, the Tiger of Summer.
Hood	Lord of Death in the Malazan pantheon, cold and implacable, presiding over the realm to which all souls eventually pass.<br>
Itkovian	Shield Anvil of the Grey Swords, the mercenary order sworn to Fener’s Reve, stationed in Capustan during the Pannion War. Part of the faith’s triumvirate alongside Mortal Sword Brukhalian and Destriant Karnadas, he embodies the compassionate arm of the order — bearing the grief and suffering of those who fall in the faith’s service so it does not pass unwitnessed.<br>
Jen'isand Rul|Master of the Deck	An Unaligned card of the Deck of Dragons with near Ascendant power.
Kilava Onass|Kilava	Renegade Imass Bonecaster and Soletaken panther, sister to Onos T’oolan, who defied the Ritual of Tellann and walks the world in her own quest for redemption.<br>
Menandore	Sister Dawn, a blinding Eleint Soletaken goddess born of Osserc and T’iam, predatory and ambitious, who hunted Scabandari’s soul and ensnared Udinaas in Reaper’s Gale.<br>
Nerruse	Lady of Calm Seas and Fair Winds, sea goddess of the Ruse and reputed daughter of Mael, invoked alongside her brother Beru for safe passage.<br>
Old Man Moon	Tattooed Jacuruku hermit whose life is bound to the moon’s phases; a wiry healer strong enough to haul armored Yakshaka and a servant of Ardata’s domain.<br>
Oponn	The twin Jesters of Chance, Ascendants, and an Unaligned card in the Deck of Dragons. The twins were male and female. When he pushed bad luck followed, while when she pulled, good fortune smiled. Interfering in the lives of mortals was a game they conducted for their own entertainment and a way to disrupt the plans of other Gods. At the same time the tension of their dual nature was part of a never-ending personal game between themselves. The male twin was described as a young man with a thin, pale, expressionless face. He was clothed in loose, white and gold, foppish silk clothing. His slim female counterpart had blonde hair with a reddish tint and wore gaudy silks and a shimmering purple cape.
Osserc|Osseric|Osric|Liossercal|Brother Light	Also known as Lord of the Sky and Champion of High House Light, god of the Tiste Liosan people and son of Father Light. A tall figure with pale skin, wavy silver hair streaked with gold, and silver eyes licked by gold. His Soletaken dragon form features glittering silver and gold scales, rivaling Anomander Rake in size. Commands the Kurald Thyrllan warren and describes his godship pragmatically: "The Liosan worship themselves... I happen to be a convenient figurehead." Self-centered, withdrawn, and reluctant to engage with the mortal world, he authored or inspired Osric's Visions, a sacred Liosan text. Fought Anomander Rake centuries earlier, confronted Sister Spite, sealed the gates to Starvald Demelain, and later became trapped in a sword before escaping. Father of L'oric.<br>
Poliel	Mistress of Pestilence, the Grey Goddess of disease and sister to healer Soliel, radiating a venomous fog that withers all around her.<br>
Ruthan Gudd	Close-mouthed captain of the Malazan 14th from Strike Island, survivor of an Azath’s fall and bearer of memories older than empires, able to wear a Stormrider’s form in battle.<br>
Shadowthrone|Ammanas|Kellanved	Also called Ammanas and once the mortal Emperor Kellanved, this Dal Honese mage co-founded the Malazan Empire with Dancer before vanishing into the Deadhouse and staging his own assassination. Ascending to seize the Throne of Shadow, he shares dominion of the Warren with Cotillion, commands its Hounds, and manipulates the High House Shadow and the Deck of Dragons through multilayered plots that reach across continents and elder warrens. His hunched, twitching presence masks encyclopedic knowledge of forgotten paths and an unrelenting drive to outmaneuver rival gods—from opposing the Crippled God to nudging mortal empires from behind the veil.<br>
Sheltatha Lore	Daughter Dusk, Tiste Edur Protectress and Eleint Soletaken, daughter of Scabandari who shifts alliances with her cousins Menandore and Sukul Ankhadu.<br>
Silchas Ruin	Albino Tiste Andii Soletaken whose bone-white dragon form earned him the name White Crow; brother to Anomander Rake and branded "the Betrayer" by the Edur.<br>
Sister of Cold Nights|Sister Night	Ancient Elder Goddess maintaining familial connections with K'rul and Draconus. Unusually tall with short unkempt black hair, pale long face with flat features, large luminous eyes, and severe expression. Wore stained, ragged traveling clothes and was fascinated by human accomplishment despite mortal limitations.<br>
Spite	Sister Spite, ash-skinned Eleint sorceress, daughter of Draconus and sister to Envy, a former agent of the Nameless Ones with a taste for manipulation and destruction.<br>
Stormy	Red-bearded Falari marine who served in the Malazan Coastal Guard, formerly an Adjutant to Cartheron Crust in the Malaz 1st Army under the Old Guard. Possessed bright blue eyes and a straightforward, martial approach to problems. Along with his lifelong friend Gesler, he was among the last members of the Old Guard's Boar Cult. His name reportedly derived from the dark clouds of his demeanor.<br>
Sukul Ankhadu	Dapple, the fickle Tiste Edur Eleint goddess with piebald skin, daughter of Osserc and T’iam, feared for luring prey before veering to hunt as a dragon.<br>
T'iam|Tiama|Tiam|T'matha	Elder Goddess and Mother of Dragons whose chaotic blood birthed the Eleint and granted the Tiste their Soletaken dragon forms.<br>
T'riss	The Queen of Dreams, also called the Enchantress, ruling High House Life and wandering the realms to intervene in visions and divinations.<br>
Togg	Wolf of Winter, ancient war god and mate to Fanderay, joint holder of the Beast Throne once lost in Chaos and famed for his one-eyed, silver-tipped lupine form.<br>
Trake|Treach	The Tiger of Summer and Beast of War, a First Hero soletaken tiger whose mind frayed over ages yet still answers warriors’ calls to battle.<br>
Truth	Young Falari recruit who served in the Malazan Coastal Guard under Corporal Gesler. Described as a gangly young man with startling blue eyes, possessing attractive features and a vulnerable demeanor. He belonged to one of the final remnants of the forbidden Boar Cult within the Malazan Military.<br>
Dryjhna|Whirlwind Goddess	A divine entity that inhabits the desert region of Raraku within the Seven Cities continent. She served as the spiritual catalyst for the apocalyptic event known as the Whirlwind and the subsequent rebellion bearing that name, revered with considerable devotion among the peoples of Seven Cities. Her earthly representative was the prophetess Sha'ik, prophesied to open the Holy Book of Dryjhna and raise the whirlwind. The primary covered walkway in the city of Hissar was designated in her honor, demonstrating the scope of her cultural significance.<br>
Whiskeyjack|Bird that Steals	A veteran commander of the Bridgeburners, he was a former protégé of Dassem Ultor. He commanded the Malazan 2nd Army and, at different times, the Malazan 3rd Army. He was also a sergeant in the 9th Squad of the Bridgeburners. His leadership, sacrifice, and mythic stature raise him close to the realm of Ascendants in memory and story.<br>
Wolves of Winter	Pack-aspect of the reunited wolf gods Togg and Fanderay upon claiming the Beast Throne: ancient predators whose winter howl carries war’s ferocity and the cold, relentless hunt of the Beast Hold.<br>
